[Clusters of cases of hantavirus infections, like the one in Bolivia, are unusual in the Americas. Just one cluster of cases has been reported in North America. There was a cluster of cases in Yosemite National Park, California in 2012, when 10 confirmed patients came from 3 states: California (8), West Virginia (1), and Pennsylvania (1). Of these, 9 patients had typical symptoms of HPS, and one lacked respiratory symptoms; 3 died. These individuals were exposed in a permanent campsite in the park where the deer mice (_Peromyscus maniculatus_) were living between the walls of double-walled tents (see Hantavirus update 2012 - Americas (38): USA (CA) 20121121.1418786).

ProMED thanks Dr Clement for his insightful overview and discussion of hantavirus cases in Europe and the Americas. His point of naming infections for the virus that causes them rather than the syndromes they cause is well taken. Inclusion of Seoul virus in diagnostic tests for suspected hantavirus infections around the world, including the Americas, should be adopted routinely. - Mod.TY

HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of Bolivia: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=6113050,38272]
